Taken from - http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONF-2328?focusedCommentId=117618#action_117618

"Also, it would be useful if there was a way to search by group membership. For example, content edited/created by any member of a group would be returned. This capability could be limited to administrators."

Take the following sentence as an example:

{code}
Visit my page at http://foo.bar
{code}

Then, text-format the whole sentence.

* In wiki markup editor:

{code}
*Visit my page at http://foo.bar*
{code}

* In Rich Text Editor, make the whole sentence bold.

As a result, the text-formatting will not be applied to the sentence. Confluence only auto-renders the link within the sentence.

Can be reproduced with other auto-rendered links: 

{code}
http://
ftp://
file:
mailto: 
{code}

This issue has been created regarding [Forum entry|http://forums.atlassian.com/thread.jspa?messageID=257278420&#257278420] as well as a request from an user attempting to write a SSO authenticator

bq. I wrote an SSO authenticator that creates confluence users on the fly as they come to our confluence instance for the first time and at this time I assign them to groups based on their roles stored on our identity server. This was working fine until we upgraded to Confluence 2.7 where the {{addMembership()}} implementation was modified to check if the current user is an *admin*. Since the current user is the actual user that is logging in for the first time, the {{addMembership()}} call fails.

The workaround for the above request would be to add the following two arguments to the {{addMemebership}} method:
* {{group.getName()}}
* {{user.getName();}}

The {{DefaultUserAccessor}} implements {{UserAccessor}} inside the *Bucket* where permissions are checked inside the {{addMembership}} method.

{code}
public void addMembership(Group group, User user)
    {
        if (!permissionManager.hasPermission(AuthenticatedUserThreadLocal.getUser(), Permission.EDIT, group))
            throw new InsufficientPrivilegeException(AuthenticatedUserThreadLocal.getUsername());

        super.addMembership(group, user);
    }
{code}

The implemented *Confluence* interface has two methods overwriting the default. 
{code}
public void addMembership(Group group, User user)
    {
        try
        {
            getGroupManager().addMembership(group, user);
        }
        catch (EntityException e)
        {
            log.error(e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    public void addMembership(String groupname, String username)
    {
        try
        {
            Group group = getGroupManager().getGroup(groupname);
            User user = getUserManager().getUser(username);

            addMembership(group, user);
        }
        catch (EntityException e)
        {
            log.error(e);
        }
    }
{code}

It looks like one of the javascripts in Confluence 2.8 is generating a URI to an image that doesn't exist. The URI follows this pattern:
{code}
/display/<SPACE_KEY>/undefined/images/border/spacer.gif
{code}

We see a lot of HTTP 404 like this in our logs from these URIs. This is a concern because 404s are slowing down the browser as well as the server (due to CONF-9050).

